# ChiefOS Project Rules

ChiefOS is a personal operating system for managing email, calendar, tasks, declutter, planning, prioritization, and intentional workflows. The founder is validating the product personally before possibly evolving it into a freemium SaaS platform.

## Product Guardrails

- Prioritize calm, clear, trustworthy workflows.
- Reduce cognitive load and avoid overwhelming the user.
- Prefer usefulness over feature complexity.
- Keep CTAs visually obvious and aligned with the user's next best action.
- Treat empty states, loading states, previews, and rollback paths as part of the product experience.

## Engineering Guardrails

- Favor simple, production-safe changes.
- Keep changes small and reviewable.
- Avoid unnecessary rewrites, broad refactors, and duplicated systems.
- Preserve existing Gmail and calendar integrations unless explicitly changing them.
- Do not introduce paid infrastructure, especially paid Vercel features, unless explicitly approved.
- Prefer user-local-time scheduling when possible.

## AI Workflow Guardrails

- Identify likely files before editing.
- Create concise plans for multi-file, risky, ambiguous, or user-facing behavior changes.
- Route high-risk work through the relevant specialist review instead of relying on a single implementation pass.
- Include confidence, assumptions, risks, unresolved questions, and untested areas in non-trivial handoffs.
- Use handoffs when context gets long, ownership changes, or a fresh conversation would be clearer.
- Preserve architectural clarity and avoid AI-generated spaghetti code.
- Keep durable workflow instructions in `.cursor/`; keep transient task details in plans or handoffs.